{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QLDCi5acXRtnqzrqmUxUEW","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Rewrite Acceptance Playbook (Spec-Only Phase)\n2\t\n3\t## Goal\n4\t\n5\tProvide a repeatable way to validate spec quality before implementation begins.\n6\t\n7\tCovered specs:\n8\t\n9\t1. `bridge-mode-contract.md`\n10\t2. `agent-triggers-contract.md`\n11\t3. `chicago-mcp-contract.md`\n12\t4. `teammem-contract.md`\n13\t5. `ultraplan-contract.md`\n14\t6. IME acceptance requirements in `acceptance-spec.md` section 5.4\n15\t\n16\t## 1. Spec QA Checklist\n17\t\n18\tFor each contract doc, verify:\n19\t\n20\t1. At least 6 code evidence anchors with file references.\n21\t2. Crate boundary section exists and is consistent with `README.md`.\n22\t3. Service trait section exists with explicit method signatures.\n23\t4. Error taxonomy section exists with policy/runtime distinction where applicable.\n24\t5. Constants classification section exists.\n25\t6. Acceptance test matrix includes contract + integration + CLI/security tests.\n26\t7. If user input is involved, IME scenarios (preedit/commit/delete/cursor width) are explicitly tested.\n27\t\n28\t## 2. Cross-Spec Consistency Checks\n29\t\n30\tRun document review checks:\n31\t\n32\t1. Error naming style is stable (`*Error` enums, deterministic category names).\n33\t2. Gate and entitlement wording is fail-closed by default.\n34\t3. State machines define terminal states and forbidden transitions.\n35\t4. Remote side-effect features include orphan/session cleanup rules.\n36\t5. No policy logic is placed in runtime adapter sections.\n37\t6. Text input behavior does not assume byte-length editing for CJK input.\n38\t\n39\t## 3. Readiness Gates Before Coding\n40\t\n41\tAll must pass:\n42\t\n43\t1. `acceptance-spec.md` reflects all active contract docs.\n44\t2. `spec-iterations.md` status matches actual document completion.\n45\t3. Each contract has explicit P0 acceptance cases.\n46\t4. Open-risk list is recorded and owner assigned.\n47\t5. IME mandatory cases are listed with platform coverage and expected results.\n48\t\n49\t## 4. Output of Spec Review Round\n50\t\n51\tAt the end of each review round, produce:\n52\t\n53\t1. Passed checks count.\n54\t2. Failed checks with owner and due date.\n55\t3. Waivers with expiry date.\n56\t\n57\tThis ensures implementation starts from auditable, testable specifications.\n58\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01W5T7riSnQ6Hs4WmL3e6Z9H","session_id":"e9f8098c-603d-4cfe-8b30-43f06752a5e5","uuid":"177a026c-4c56-44e5-97e1-10d08e33d812","timestamp":"2026-04-02T14:28:19.309Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MfHMBBQpsv2xoVN6A8PokT","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Rust Rewrite Acceptance Specification\n2\t\n3\t## 1. Scope\n4\t\n5\tThis specification defines measurable acceptance criteria for full migration from TypeScript/Bun to Rust workspace architecture.\n6\t\n7\tIn scope:\n8\t\n9\t1. Workspace architecture (`crates/`, `bins/`, `xtask/`).\n10\t2. Service boundary migration and ownership.\n11\t3. Command/tool/runtime parity.\n12\t4. Security, observability, and operability readiness.\n13\t\n14\tOut of scope:\n15\t\n16\t1. New product features not present in legacy behavior.\n17\t2. Cosmetic UX redesign unrelated to parity or maintainability.\n18\t\n19\t## 2. Architecture Acceptance\n20\t\n21\t### 2.1 Workspace Structure\n22\t\n23\tMust exist:\n24\t\n25\t1. Root `Cargo.toml` with workspace members for all runtime and service crates.\n26\t2. `crates/` with at least the core crates declared in the rewrite plan.\n27\t3. `bins/app-cli` binary crate as primary CLI entrypoint.\n28\t4. `xtask` crate for release/build/check automation.\n29\t\n30\tAcceptance command:\n31\t\n32\t```bash\n33\tcargo metadata --format-version 1 > /tmp/rust-workspace-metadata.json\n34\t```\n35\t\n36\tPass condition:\n37\t\n38\t1. Command exits `0`.\n39\t2. Metadata includes expected members and no duplicate package names.\n40\t\n41\t### 2.2 Dependency Direction Rules\n42\t\n43\tMust hold:\n44\t\n45\t1. `core-domain` does not depend on runtime or UI crates.\n46\t2. `api-types` does not depend on runtime crates.\n47\t3. `bins/*` contain composition only, with no domain logic implementation.\n48\t\n49\tAcceptance mechanism:\n50\t\n51\t1. Static dependency check script in `xtask`.\n52\t2. PR check that fails on forbidden edges.\n53\t\n54\tPass condition:\n55\t\n56\t1. All forbidden edges report zero findings.\n57\t\n58\t## 3. Constants Governance Acceptance\n59\t\n60\tConstants must be classified into exactly one category:\n61\t\n62\t1. Contract constants in `api-types`.\n63\t2. Configurable defaults in `config`.\n64\t3. Domain invariants in `core-domain`.\n65\t4. Runtime-local constants in owning runtime crate.\n66\t5. UI-only constants in `ui-tui`.\n67\t\n68\tAcceptance mechanism:\n69\t\n70\t1. `docs/rust-rewrite/constants-policy.md` exists and is referenced by crate READMEs.\n71\t2. Lint/check script blocks new cross-domain `constants` dumping patterns.\n72\t\n73\tPass condition:\n74\t\n75\t1. No unresolved constants classification exceptions in release branch.\n76\t\n77\t## 4. Functional Parity Acceptance\n78\t\n79\t### 4.1 Command Parity\n80\t\n81\tFor each supported CLI command group:\n82\t\n83\t1. Success path parity test.\n84\t2. Validation error parity test.\n85\t3. Permission or auth failure parity test (where applicable).\n86\t\n87\tPass condition:\n88\t\n89\t1. `P0` command set reaches 100% parity tests passing.\n90\t2. `P1` command set reaches at least 95% parity tests passing.\n91\t\n92\t### 4.2 Tool Runtime Parity\n93\t\n94\tFor each migrated tool category:\n95\t\n96\t1. Deterministic output parity test.\n97\t2. Timeout/cancellation behavior parity test.\n98\t3. Structured error mapping parity test.\n99\t\n100\tPass condition:\n101\t\n102\t1. No open `P0` parity gaps.\n103\t2. Documented waiver for any accepted `P1` differences.\n104\t\n105\t## 5. Non-Functional Acceptance\n106\t\n107\t### 5.1 Reliability\n108\t\n109\tPass condition:\n110\t\n111\t1. CLI smoke suite passes for 30 consecutive CI runs on main branch.\n112\t2. No crash-loop defects in soak test window.\n113\t\n114\t### 5.2 Performance\n115\t\n116\tBenchmarks must be captured for representative flows:\n117\t\n118\t1. Cold startup time.\n119\t2. Median command latency.\n120\t3. Memory footprint under sustained interaction.\n121\t\n122\tPass condition:\n123\t\n124\t1. No metric regresses more than agreed budget (default: 10%) without approved waiver.\n125\t\n126\t### 5.3 Security\n127\t\n128\tPass condition:\n129\t\n130\t1. Dependency checks pass (`cargo audit` and policy checks).\n131\t2. Secret scanning passes.\n132\t3. Permission boundary tests pass for runtime-sensitive operations.\n133\t\n134\t### 5.4 Input Method Editor (IME) Correctness\n135\t\n136\tScope:\n137\t\n138\t1. Interactive CLI/TUI text input behavior under Chinese IME composition and candidate selection.\n139\t\n140\tRequired behavior:\n141\t\n142\t1. Composition text (preedit) and committed text are managed as separate states.\n143\t2. Backspace/delete operates on grapheme clusters, not bytes.\n144\t3. Cursor movement and rendering use display width rules, preventing full-width/half-width drift.\n145\t\n146\tPass condition:\n147\t\n148\t1. No visual corruption after candidate selection followed by delete/backspace.\n149\t2. Cursor position remains aligned with rendered text during and after composition.\n150\t3. Same test cases pass on macOS input methods used by the team.\n151\t\n152\t## 6. Observability and Operations Acceptance\n153\t\n154\tMust exist:\n155\t\n156\t1. Structured logging with request/session correlation IDs.\n157\t2. Error taxonomy documented and mapped to user-facing exit behavior.\n158\t3. Operational runbook for startup, shutdown, failure triage, and rollback.\n159\t\n160\tPass condition:\n161\t\n162\t1. On-call dry run can complete top 5 incident playbooks without undocumented steps.\n163\t\n164\t## 7. CI/CD Acceptance Gates\n165\t\n166\tRequired pipeline checks:\n167\t\n168\t```bash\n169\tcargo fmt --check\n170\tcargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -D warnings\n171\tcargo nextest run --workspace\n172\tcargo test --workspace --doc\n173\t```\n174\t\n175\tRecommended additional checks:\n176\t\n177\t```bash\n178\tcargo audit\n179\tcargo deny check\n180\t```\n181\t\n182\tPass condition:\n183\t\n184\t1. All required checks are green on release candidate tag.\n185\t2. IME regression suite is green on release candidate tag.\n186\t\n187\t## 8. Documentation Acceptance\n188\t\n189\tRequired artifacts:\n190\t\n191\t1. `docs/rust-rewrite/README.md` (architecture + migration strategy).\n192\t2. `docs/rust-rewrite/constants-policy.md` (classification policy).\n193\t3. `docs/rust-rewrite/adr/*` for boundary decisions.\n194\t4. Operator runbook and release checklist.\n195\t5. `docs/rust-rewrite/multi-agent-orchestration-contract.md` for coordinator fan-out/synthesis behavior.\n196\t\n197\tPass condition:\n198\t\n199\t1. Every runtime crate has a README with purpose, dependencies, and owner.\n200\t\n201\t## 9. Final Sign-Off Checklist\n202\t\n203\tRelease sign-off requires all below:\n204\t\n205\t1. Architecture acceptance passed.\n206\t2. Constants governance acceptance passed.\n207\t3. Functional parity acceptance passed.\n208\t4. Non-functional acceptance passed.\n209\t5. CI/CD gates passed.\n210\t6. Documentation acceptance passed.\n211\t7. Stakeholder sign-off from Engineering, SRE/Platform, and Security.\n212\t\n213\tAny exception must be recorded as a dated waiver with owner and expiry date.\n214\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01W5T7riSnQ6Hs4WmL3e6Z9H","session_id":"e9f8098c-603d-4cfe-8b30-43f06752a5e5","uuid":"522ccfba-2394-4e65-9494-6694cf1fff30","timestamp":"2026-04-02T14:28:19.308Z"}
